{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chart-page-js","path":"/dot-chart","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>replaces the bar with a line-and-dot combination. Dot charts may be useful in large data sets where bars would be too thin. For improved readability, the dots are typically of a more high-contrast color than the lines. 1. <em>Dot chart</em> uses a dot to represent a data point and otherwise is equivalent to a bar chart in terms of a reader's ability to compare values.<sup id=\"fnref-1\"><a href=\"#fn-1\" class=\"footnote-ref\">1</a></sup> Dot charts allow for a more elegant way of displaying large data sets.<sup id=\"fnref-2\"><a href=\"#fn-2\" class=\"footnote-ref\">2</a></sup> The dot chart is not to be confused with the <a href=\"/dot-plot\">dot plot</a>, a statistical graphic that shows the distribution of individual observations represented as dots at regular intervals.</p>\n<!--more-->\n<h2 id=\"references\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#references\" aria-label=\"references permalink\" class=\"anchorLink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>References</h2>\n<div class=\"footnotes\">\n<hr>\n<ol>\n<li id=\"fn-1\">\n<p>Cairo, Alberto. <a href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=xwjhh6Wu-VUC\"><em>The Functional Art: An introduction to information graphics and visualization.</em></a> New Riders, 2012. p. 126-127.</p>\n<a href=\"#fnref-1\" class=\"footnote-backref\">↩</a>\n</li>\n<li id=\"fn-2\">\n<p>Robbins, Naomi B. <a href=\"(http://perceptualedge.com/articles/b-eye/dot_plots.pdf)\">\"Dot Plots: A Useful Alternative to Bar Charts.\"</a> <em>Business Intelligence Network Newsletter</em> (2006). p.3</p>\n<a href=\"#fnref-2\" class=\"footnote-backref\">↩</a>\n</li>\n</ol>\n</div>","excerpt":"replaces the bar with a line-and-dot combination. Dot charts may be useful in large data sets where bars would be too thin. For improved…","overview":"<p>replaces the bar with a line-and-dot combination. Dot charts may be useful in large data sets where bars would be too thin. For improved…</p>","fields":{"variationOf":"bar-chart"},"frontmatter":{"title":"dot chart","synonyms":["lollipop chart"],"functions":["comparison","change over time"],"visualizationTechniques":[{"techniqueId":"AXI","informationType":"quantity","axisDirection":"vertical"},{"techniqueId":"SBA","informationType":"quantity","axisDirection":null}],"informationTypes":null,"axisDirections":null,"examples":null,"tools":null},"fileInfo":{"__typename":"File","modifiedTime":"07/24/2023"}},"coverImage":{"publicURL":"/static/0ddb2d53ed0d74933a074e00a64af9dd/cover.png"},"anatomyImage":null,"site":{"siteMetadata":{"siteUrl":"https://graphopedia.xyz"}},"exampleImages":{"edges":[]},"variations":{"edges":[]},"parentChart":{"excerpt":"displays the relationship of a category to a numeric variable as the height a rectangle bar.  Each bar represents a single number. Bar charts compare discrete numbers and not continuously changing data. The bar chart consists of a categorical X-axis…","overview":"<p>displays the relationship of a category to a numeric variable as the height a rectangle bar.  Each bar represents a single number. Bar…</p>","fields":{"slug":"bar-chart"},"frontmatter":{"title":"bar chart"}},"allVisualizationTechniquesYaml":{"edges":[{"node":{"id":"PIC","name":"picturing"}},{"node":{"id":"MAP","name":"mapping"}},{"node":{"id":"AXI","name":"positioning along a coordinate axis"}},{"node":{"id":"EXT","name":"extending along a coordinate axis"}},{"node":{"id":"DIV","name":"diverging